<paper id="1483793314"><title>Fast RSA-Type Cryptosystems Using N-Adic Expansion</title><year>1997</year><authors><author org="NTT Software Laboratories" id="2051837146">Tsuyoshi Takagi</author></authors><n_citation>15</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>36827820</reference><reference>1515644111</reference><reference>1536986722</reference><reference>1557014463</reference><reference>1599079796</reference><reference>1660562555</reference><reference>1749471906</reference><reference>1979366382</reference><reference>1991728011</reference><reference>1996360405</reference><reference>2009635047</reference><reference>2016718197</reference><reference>2085856764</reference><reference>2108104892</reference><reference>2166780626</reference><reference>2168581558</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0052249</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.70292">Hybrid cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.62043">Merkle–Hellman knapsack cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.40249">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.61932">Goldwasser–Micali cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.39141">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.61359">Benaloh cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.61412">Deterministic encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.40921">Arithmetic</keyword><keyword weight="0.40073">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.66125">Cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.6314">Threshold cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.588">Plaintext</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We propose two RSA-type cryptosystems using n-adic expansion, where n is the public key. These cryptosystems can have more than one block as a plaintext space, and the decrypting process is faster than any other multi-block RSA-type cryptosystem ever reported. Deciphering the entire plaintext of this system is as intractable as breaking the RSA cryptosystem or factoring. Even if a message is several times longer than a public key n, we can encrypt the message fast without repeatedly using the secret key cryptosystem.</abstract></paper>